<DOC><DOCNO> AP890216-0288 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1808EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Lufthansa-Airbus     02-16 0221</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Lufthansa-Airbus,0233</SECOND><HEAD>Lufthansa To Buy Up To 30 Planes In $3 Billion Deal</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lufthansa German Airlines has agreed to buy upto 30 commerical aircraft from Airbus Industrie, a Europeanconsortium, in an estimated $3 billion deal, Airbus officials saidThursday.   The order gives another boost to the commercial jet industry.Earlier this month, American Airlines signed a 142-plane, estimated$7 billion deal with McDonnell Douglas Corp.   Lufthansa plans to use the new plans to replace uts fleet ofDC10-30 aircraft, enabling the airline to offer most nonstop routesfrom West Germany to the United States, South America and the FarEast, Airbus said.   The contract, signed Wednesday, calls for Lufthansa to buy 15Airbus A340 aircraft for delivery between September 1992 and March1994.   Lufthansa will receive both A4340-200s, which seat 222passengers, and A340-300s, which have 256-seat cabins. Both versionsare powered by CFM International CFM56-5C-2 engines.   According to the contract, Lufthansa will decide later on whetherto purchase 15 more planes.   With the Lufthansa order, Airbus now has firm orders, options andcommitments for 110 A340 aircraft, the consortium said.   Last year, $48.5 billion in new planes were ordered, the highesttotal ever. Industry officials estimate that the demand to replaceaging aircraft could push annual sales to $450 billion by the year2005.</TEXT></DOC>